    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: Bundled payments</title>
    <updated>2023-06-23T01:47:14.217949+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2023-June/003977.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Lightning Network's BOLT-11 may soon receive an update that allows invoices to contain two bundled payments. This proposal by Thomas Voegtlin aims to benefit non-custodial services such as Submarine swaps and JIT channels where prepayment of mining fees is required before exchange takes place. The feature would enable service providers to offer non-custodial services, leveling the playing field between them. However, some experts have expressed concerns that it may take years for this update to be widely adopted.Matt Corallo responded to Thomas's proposal, stating that he believes it would be challenging to get any new interoperable changes into BOLT-11. Instead, he suggests standardizing the OMs for more private transactions. Matt believes that specifying a "standard" way of doing swaps built on OMs would enable services like ACINQ to become fully non-custodial, benefiting the pay-to-open service. The proposed bundled payment feature in BOLT-11 requires senders to understand that the payment will lead to a channel creation or a splice on the receiver end. The feature requires all existing software used by senders to be updated. The semantics of bundled payments require the receiver to wait until all the HTLCs of both payments have arrived before fulfilling the HTLCs of the pre-payment. If the primary payment does not arrive, they should fail the pre-payment with a MPP timeout. Once the HTLCs of both payments have arrived, the receiver can fulfill the HTLCs of the prepayment and broadcast their on-chain transaction.In the case of Submarine swaps, dedicated client software like Loop by Lightning Labs can handle prepayments, but competitors who do not require a dedicated wallet, such as the Boltz exchange, cannot do so. Boltz is vulnerable to DoS attacks, where the attacker forces them to pay on-chain fees. Thus, competitors need to show one invoice to be paid simultaneously, which is impractical. Regarding Thomas's question about the distinction between splice-out and submarine swaps, Matt said that submarine swaps make it possible to add receiving capacity to a channel. In conclusion, the proposed feature in BOLT-11 could revolutionize non-custodial services provided by lightning service providers if adopted. However, its implementation may take time, and some experts suggest alternative methods such as standardizing the OMs for more privacy in transactions.</summary>
